-- French Stocks Advance, Paced by Peugeot, Ubisoft Entertainment and Zodiac
-- Sarah Jones
-- 2010-07-13T16:08:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-13/french-stocks-advance-paced-by-peugeot-ubisoft-entertainment-and-zodiac.html

          
          
             France’s benchmark CAC 40 Index
advanced 70.1, or 2 percent, to 3,637.76 in Paris, a sixth day
of gains. The SBF 120 index climbed 1.9 percent today.  
 The following is a list of companies whose shares either
rose or fell in the French capital. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  
 Bureau Veritas SA  (BVI FP) gained 1.62 pence, or 3.4
percent, to 49.16 euros after BofA-Merrill Lynch Global Research
upgraded the world’s second-largest goods inspection company to
“buy.”  
 Esker SA  (ESK FP) rallied 16 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 7.11
euros after the fax-software supplier reported higher revenue.
Second-quarter revenue rose to 8.53 million euros ($10.7
million) from 6.48 million euros a year earlier.  
 Lagardere SCA  (MMB FP) gained 1.04 euros, or 4 percent, to
26.87 after Natixis raised its recommendation for the shares to
“buy” from “neutral.”  
 PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP) increased 1.22 euros, or 5.3
percent, to 24.37, pacing gains in European automaker shares
after Bayerische Motoren Werke AG raised its profit forecast.
 Renault SA  (RNO FP) also advanced, climbing 1.44 euros, or 4.2
percent, to 35.28.  
 Separately, La Tribune reported Peugeot will begin offering
a new sedan, the 508, that will replace both its 407 and its
top-of-the-line 607. The newspaper did not say where it got the
information.  
 Ubisoft Entertainment SA  (UBI FP) jumped 98.2 cents, or 15
percent, to 7.35 euros after Europe’s biggest video-game
producer almost doubled first-quarter revenue to 160 million
euros on sales of its Splinter Cell and Assassin’s Creed titles.
The company also confirmed its forecast of a return to
profitable growth this year.  
 Zodiac Aerospace SA  (ZC FP) gained 1.89 euros, or 4.4
percent, to 44.5 euros, extending yesterday’s 7.1 percent rally.
La Tribune reported that Safran SA isn’t considering a hostile
takeover for Zodiac. The newspaper cited comments by Jean-Pierre
Cojan, who heads Safran’s strategy and development.  
